Trees provide unquantifiable benefits such as improving the climate, regulating stream and river flows, conserving and protecting the soil and providing stable habitats for wildlife, according to experts.Celtis africana is also an excellent shade tree because it is evergreen. For bird lovers, its fruits attract many.The wood of Celtis africana is heavy and good for making planks, shelving, yokes, tool handles, railway sleepers and furniture.Propagation of Celtis africana is mainly through seed, which costs Sh3,500 a kilo at the Kenya Forestry Research Institute centres. Celtis africana is commonly known as white stinkwood because of the unpleasant smell of its freshly cut wood and its pale colour.
It is native to Africa and grows in a wide range of habitats from the Coast up to 2,100 metres above sea level. 
Among its local names are Murudu (Kikuyu) and Toninwo (Tugen).



