Trees provide unquantifiable benefits such as improving the climate, regulating stream and river flows, conserving and protecting the soil and providing stable habitats for wildlife, according to experts.
The Centre for International Forest Research (CIFOR) says tree-growing is fundamental to increasing the sustainable provision of wood, as the basis to support job creation in rural areas.
In an article titled “To pant or not to plant trees” on its online Forest News website, CIFOR says growing the right trees in the right places is one of the most cost-effective actions to enhance carbon sinks and support biodiversity.





Trees are also a source of supply of building timber, poles, plywood, wood-fuel, pulp and paper.
Other commodities and services from forests and trees include fruits, oils, tannins and medicines. 
More than one purpose
Farmers should plant trees that serve more than one purpose and Celtis africana certainly is one such a tree.
Many of its parts are used in traditional African medicine. The pounded bark is used to treat fever, headache and general malaise.
A leaf decoction is applied to sore eyes. The roots are boiled and the infusion drunk to stop shaking, according to Field Guide to the Moist Forest Trees of Tanzania by Lovett J.C.; Ruffo C.K.; Gereau R.E. and Taplin J.R.D.



