The fibrous bark is often used for making ropes and cloth, according to Plant Resources of Tropical Africa.
Celtis africana is also an excellent shade tree because it is evergreen. For bird lovers, its fruits attract many.
The birds feed on the fruits and leaves and play a key role in dispersing the seeds. Its leaves are also fodder for cattle and goats.
The flowers, that appear in August to October, are pollinated by bees hence it is good for honey production, according to Trees of Southern Africa by Palmer, E. and Pitman, N. 
The wood of Celtis africana is heavy and good for making planks, shelving, yokes, tool handles, railway sleepers and furniture.
Africans have always used it to make agricultural implements and household articles like pestles, spoons, boxes and crates. 
Fairly drought-resistant
In construction, it is used for flooring, joinery, interior trim, mine props and ladders.
The wood also produces quality charcoal and firewood.
Some African communities believe the tree has magical properties and plant it in homesteads to keep evil spirits away.
Propagation
Propagation of Celtis africana is mainly through seed, which costs Sh3,500 a kilo at the Kenya Forestry Research Institute centres.



