The seedbeds should be filled with a mixture of parts of river sand and well-decomposed compost. To promote germination, seeds should be covered with a thin layer of river sand and kept moist. Under these circumstances, germination takes 15-30 days. The germination rate is up to 70 per cent.
Experts do not recommend the use of seeds collected from the ground because they are usually infested by insects, so it is best to harvest from the tree.
Celtis africana is fast-growing and fairly drought-resistant. Planted in good, rich soil and adequately watered, it can grow for up two metres a year.
